Posted @withrepost • @coreyscauldron We have a heavy Grimoire/Book of Shadows/Journal/etc. day! These podcasts are FULL of great things to put in you preferred method of recording for your practice. 

First up we have @saltywitchespodcast, talking about using magic against violence. Obviously, physical safety is number one. However, protection magic can help put your mind at ease and can help negate things. I will say, CONTENT WARNING on this one. There is conversation about Club Q and the effect it has had on the LGBTQ+ community. I will also take this time to say, marginalized content creators are allowed to be angry and express rage at the ongoing violence against them. Any comments that are hateful or disparaging toward minority groups will be deleted.

Next up, we have, @middleagedwitch talking about casting a circle. Something I had to learn the hard way, don’t use salt circles outside. You’ll salt the earth and make the soil unable to hold life in that area. I did this ONCE at an apartment, I swept my salt circle off into the grass from my patio. DON’T DO! Eli gives wonderful examples of ways to cast a circle in various material and spaces.

Then you have @madamepamita talking about Slavic Cloth magic! All about weaving and creation! The concept of how a hope is laid out magically and the use of magic in the mundane and the mundane in the magic. This one has piqued my interest in throwing my hands into spinning, the learning curve sounds fun and a protection shawl sounds like a great project!

Have a wonderful day and be sure you’re ready to write!

Baba Yaga is a Slavic Folklore Grandmother Witch who lives in an enchanted hut that moves around on one chicken leg! 
❄️From World History: “Baba Yaga is probably best known from the story Vasilissa the Beautiful in which she inadvertently frees the heroine from the tyranny of her stepmother and stepsisters but also figures in other famous tales such as The Frog Princess and Baba Yaga and the Kind-Hearted Girl in which she is cast in a similar role. A number of her tales follow the paradigm of the Cinderella story where she plays the part of the Fairy Godmother but with a decidedly sinister twist.

As she lives outside the norms of society and always by her own rules, she has come to embody the concept of feminine power and emancipation in the modern age.”

Mythology defines culture. It sets the landscape for interaction with self, community and Source.

So much culture has been lost through the dominance of suppressive religion, the voyage across oceans and the desire to assimilate. 

Many of my ancestors came to North America between 1600-1800 and there is little that remains in the passing down of old ways. 

With the exception of my maternal grandfather who was born in Postupel, an area in north eastern Ukraine that has been both Poland and Russia. He was the only elder I ever recall sharing stories of magic that he made up on the spot at my demand. I was the feature character -Sarishka- and there was always an excitedly scary witch in the woods, Baba Yaga.

The classic crone, Baba Yaga is an archetype of the sacred feminine which has been burned out of our common awareness and often marked as evil. 

Yet she is a keeper of our connection to the sacred, a steward of truth, and a guardian of our underworld landscape. We need her. She has much to teach us.

I was delighted to receive this gift from my daughter for Christmas. And as you can see am avidly practicing my cross stitch spells.

Vivian Reed as Ozma of Oz in the opening credits to the 1914 silent film THE PATCHWORK GIRL OF OZ.

L. Frank Baum’s 1904 novel “The Marvelous Land of Oz,” a sequel to “The Wonderful Wizard of Oz” (1900), features the first appearance of trans icon Ozma.
 
Ozma is a princess, and the ruler of the Land of Oz, who was cursed at birth into the body of a boy; later she must to come to terms with her true gender and take her place on the throne. Ozma is fully accepted by her friends, and the citizens of Oz, after her transition and rules the land through the rest of the books in the Oz series (There are 14 books in total by Baum).
 
Though the character of Ozma is not in the existing Oz silent films, her image exists in this happy portrait as the ruler/icon of the series. Ozma’s character was on film in L. Frank Baum’s 1908 traveling film, magic lantern, and live actor multimedia “Oz” show titled, “Fairylogue and Radio-Plays”. Her transition from the character of Tip into Princess Ozma was said to be one of the big special-effect features in their telling of “The Land of Oz”.

Baum used the traveling show to promote his Oz books. Unfortunately, the show was too expensive to keep going and Baum had to pass over the film rights to the company that was backing him. The Oz films from the traveling show were lost in the process – though, their content is known because the scripts, and magic lantern slides, still exist.

Ok, guys.
A lot happened tonight and this morning. First, we have a new tradition - a new air strike every night. We woke up at 2.30 AM due to the HUGE explosions right above our heads. They were powerful enough to start the cars' safety systems start working all around. But I can tell you that Patriots are a very effective weapon, and all the targets were shot down; in the morning, people began finding their parts on the streets. The most amazing thing is that Danny didn't wake up! The same applies to my mom - when I came to the living room to ask how is she, I thought that another drone had flown inside the apartment so loudly she snored:) Lucky people, what can I say! 
Despite the sleepless and a very stressful night, we did our work very well. Seven grannies received your help, including those who waited for it very long. 
First, I want to point to the heartbreaking story of Zinaida Yakovlevna, an 81-year-old refugee from destroyed Orekhov. See the video! We are the only organization that helps her at the moment; this is why we don't have a chance to fail!
Tamara Anatoliyevna. She was so happy that she cried - look at her emotional photo! By the time of our visit, she didn't have money even for bread. 
Margarita Mihaylovna. I was waiting for Danny to visit her cause he wanted to play with Nyusha so much! He even hopped outside to get him some grass cats usually eat.
Nina Mihailovna! I will remind you that this cute and smiling granny is 95!
Guys, we are doing well at the moment — 29 grannies for now. If we will help 40, it means that the intervals won't be stretched more this week. And the next week, we can think about how to get them back to standard step by step. Cause it really painful to see the grannies who look at the bread as if it's an eighth miracle. Please help us!

The Kumpo is a masquerade found among the Jola, an ethnic group found in The Gambia and Southern Senegal. Masquerade in Africa symbolises unity, as all ethnic and religious groups celebrate together through Masquerade. This resonates across West Africa and its Diaspora as a form of cultural resistance.

The Kumpo mask is made up of thin dried palm leaves which are beige in colour and cover the dancer from head to toe. The other feature is a stick which is secured to the performer’s head which he uses to spin almost magically in fast gyrating circles while being accompanied by an ensemble of metal bells, singers and drums.
